cron</i>. The term included the heron until the introduction of a separate word for the latter in the 14th century.","Manx: see   Craine  .","Dutch: variant of   Krane   ‘crane’."],"variants":[{"name":"Craine","meanings":["Manx: shortened form of Gaelic <b>Mac (Giolla) Ciaráin</b> ‘son of (the devotee of) <i>Ciarán</i>’, a personal name based on a diminutive of Gaelic <i>ciar</i>, Manx <i>keeir</i> ‘black’. The place Ballacraine on the Isle of Man means ‘Craine's farm’."]},{"name":"Corn","meanings":["English: nickname from Old English <i>corn</i>, a metathesized form of <i>cran</i> ‘crane’ (see   Crane  ).","English: metonymic occupational name for a maker or user of hand mills, Old English <i>cweorn</i>.","Americanized form of German, Dutch, Czech, or Jewish   Korn  , or a shortened form of any of the composite names formed with this element."]},{"name":"Crank","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): from Middle English <i>cranke</i> ‘lively, lusty, vigorous’, hence a nickname for a cheerful, boisterous, or merry person.","English: possibly in some cases, a nickname from <i>cranuc</i>, a diminutive of Middle English <i>cran</i> ‘crane’ (see   Crane  ).","Possibly an Americanized form of German <b>Kranke</b>: from Low German <i>Kraneke</i> ‘crane’, applied to someone thought to resemble the bird in some way, or a nickname for a poor physical specimen, from Middle High German <i>kranc</i> ‘sickly, ailing’."]},{"name":"Cran","meanings":["Scottish (Aberdeenshire): variant of English   Crane  .","Dutch: variant of <b>Kraan</b> or one of its variants, such as <b>Craane</b> and   Krane  ."]},{"name":"Cornforth","meanings":["English (North Yorkshire and Durham): habitational name from Cornforth in County Durham, named with Old English <i>corn</i>, a metathesized form of <i>cron</i>, <i>cran</i> ‘crane’ (see   Crane  ) + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Thomas Crane was born in 1255, in Henham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Thomas Crane, was 28 and his mother, Ada Kerdiston, was 25. He married Petronella Bettesley in 1273, in Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter."},"et":{"1255–":"1255–Surnud","1255–Male":"1255–Surnud","1256–1330":"1256–1330","1248–Female":"1248–Surnud","1274–Male":"1274–Surnud","1276–Female":"1276–Surnud","1278–Male":"1278–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1227–Male":"1227–Surnud","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1227":"1227","1248":"1248","1278":"1278","1256":"1256","1255":"1255","1276":"1276","1254":"1254","1330":"1330","1274":"1274","1230":"1230","1273":"1273","Stoneham, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Chilton, Stoneham, Suffolk, England":"Chilton, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Henham, Suffolk, England":"Henham, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1255–":"1255–Kuollut","1255–Male":"1255–Kuollut","1256–1330":"1256–1330","1248–Female":"1248–Kuollut","1274–Male":"1274–Kuollut","1276–Female":"1276–Kuollut","1278–Male":"1278–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1227–Male":"1227–Kuollut","1230–Female":"1230–Kuollut","1227":"1227","1248":"1248","1278":"1278","1256":"1256","1255":"1255","1276":"1276","1254":"1254","1330":"1330","1274":"1274","1230":"1230","1273":"1273","Stoneham, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Su